You might want to try to return a 
`Mono.error(new CustomError(response));` in your `handleError()` method.
This way you&#39;ve let the reactive pipeline know an error has occured and what to throw afterwards. Right now you just map to an Error object, which is not handled the same way as RuntimeExceptions.

I would also say that it is probably better to stick to `Exceptions` instead of `Errors`. Errors tend to be unrecoverable situations for the program to run (`OutOfMemoryError` for example), whereas Exceptions are just exceptional cases that _could_ be reacted to potentially (retrying for a 503 status code, or reauthenticating when you receive a 401 status code back).


Example implementation
```java
	public Mono&lt;? extends Throwable&gt; handleError(ClientResponse clientResponse) {
		String message = String.format(&quot;Service error: %s&quot;,
				clientResponse.statusCode().getReasonPhrase());
		return Mono.error(new CustomError(message));
	}
```
This is also a good answer: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53595420/correct-way-of-throwing-exceptions-with-reactor

